<DocsLayout title="Overview">
  <h1>EncodeSwarmr Documentation</h1>
  <p>
    EncodeSwarmr is a distributed video encoding orchestration platform that coordinates GPU-accelerated encoding across multiple machines. It uses a Controller-Agent architecture where a central Controller manages job queuing, scheduling, and monitoring while Agents on remote machines perform the actual encoding work.
  </p>

  <h2>Key Concepts</h2>

  <h3>Controller</h3>
  <p>
    The Controller is the central hub that runs as a single Go binary. It provides:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>A REST API (<code>/api/v1</code>) for programmatic access</li>
    <li>A React-based web dashboard for visual management</li>
    <li>A gRPC service (port 9443) for agent communication over mTLS</li>
    <li>A WebSocket event hub for real-time UI updates</li>
    <li>Job queue management with priority FIFO scheduling</li>
    <li>Script generation from templates (AviSynth/VapourSynth)</li>
    <li>Media analysis coordination (HDR detection, VMAF, scene detection)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Agents</h3>
  <p>
    Agents are worker nodes installed on machines with GPU hardware. They:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Connect to the Controller over gRPC with mTLS encryption</li>
    <li>Auto-detect GPU capabilities (NVIDIA NVENC, Intel QSV, AMD AMF)</li>
    <li>Execute encoding jobs and stream real-time progress</li>
    <li>Maintain a local SQLite journal for offline resilience</li>
    <li>Support self-upgrade with SHA-256 verified binary downloads</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Jobs</h3>
  <p>
    A job represents a single encoding task. Jobs flow through the system as follows:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>A source is registered (local path or cloud storage URI)</li>
    <li>Analysis jobs auto-queue (HDR detection, optional VMAF/scene detection)</li>
    <li>An encoding job is created with a preset and destination</li>
    <li>The Controller assigns the job to an available Agent</li>
    <li>The Agent executes the encode and streams progress back</li>
    <li>On completion, results are recorded and webhooks fire</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>System Requirements</h2>

  <h3>Controller</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Component</th><th>Requirement</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>OS</td><td>Linux (Docker recommended)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Database</td><td>PostgreSQL 16+</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Memory</td><td>512 MB minimum</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ports</td><td>8080 (HTTP), 9443 (gRPC)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Agents</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Component</th><th>Requirement</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>OS</td><td>Windows Server / Windows 10+ / Linux</td></tr>
      <tr><td>GPU</td><td>NVIDIA, Intel, or AMD with encoding support</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Network</td><td>Outbound access to Controller on port 9443</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Storage</td><td>Access to media shares (UNC/NFS)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

